When the fingers or toes are dislocated, they should be gently extended without force, and this is an easy thing.	On the treatment of dislocation of the toes. Any that are dislocated must be straightened by means of gentle extension, without violence; that is not hard but positively easy.	0.6789979
And if the dislocation is in any joint of the back of the foot, you should have the patient sit on a flat surface or on a table, upright, and place your foot on the part of the joint that protrudes, then press firmly with your foot until it returns to place; and when it is even, and nothing protrudes, place a two-headed board under the sole of the foot, then bandage it tightly, and leave it for three days, then untie it; and have him rest until he is healed.	If the dislocation be in one of the joints of the dorsum of the foot, the patient must set his foot on level ground or upon a board, standing as though walking. Then you must stand and put your foot on what protrudes of those joints, and put strong pressure upon it with your foot until it goes back and you see that it is evened out and there is no prominence at the place. Then put under the sole of his foot a flat splint with two heads to take the whole foot, and bind it on with a tight and secure bandage for three days; then loosen it; but keep him from walking for a good many days until it binds and you are sure it will not revert, God willing.	0.9103126
